# No assumptions — ask the user

When anything is unclear, **do not guess or invent requirements, names, shapes, or behavior.**
Ask the user. There is **no limit** on how many times you may ask — asking again is always
better than building the wrong thing.

## Rules

- If a requirement, API shape, data model, scope, or acceptance criterion is ambiguous, **stop
  and ask** before writing code.
- Prefer the structured question tool (multiple-choice) so the user can answer quickly; ask in
  batches when several things are unclear.
- Re-ask whenever new ambiguity appears mid-task — repeatedly if necessary.
- It is fine to ask for: missing values, intended behavior on edge cases, naming, file/module
  placement, trade-off preferences, and confirmation before destructive or scope-changing actions.
- Only proceed on a default when the user has explicitly said "use your judgement / recommended",
  and even then, **state the assumption** you made.

## Anti-pattern

> "I'll assume the endpoint returns `{ data: [...] }` and move on." ❌

> "The response shape isn't defined in `contracts/`. Should it be `{ data: [...] }` or a bare
> array? (asking before I implement)" ✅
